        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais&#44; President<lb/> of the Faculty of the Jewish Theo&#45;<lb/>&#45;logical Seminary&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>Honored Sir&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have the honor<lb/> to submit my report on the stand&#45;<lb/>&#45;ing of the Seminary classes during<lb/> the first month of the Summer term<lb/> of 5650&#45;1890 from June 15th to July 15th.<lb/>  There are at present 12 students<lb/> attending the Seminary&#44; 9 regularly<lb/> admitted and 3 awaiting admission.<lb/>  Of the regularly admitted students&#44;<lb/> one&#44; Alexander Barovsky&#44; has been<lb/> extremely irregular in his attendance<lb/> The students of the higher or Junior<lb/> class are Alex. Barovsky&#44; Joseph Hertz&#44; Sigmund Reich&#44;<lb/> Henry Speaker and David Wittenberg.<lb/>  The students of the lower or Prepar&#45;<lb/>&#45;atory class are Benjamin and Samuel<lb/> Ehrenreich&#44; Maurice Fried&#44; Max Goodman<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>regularly admitted and David Bressler&#44;<lb/> Benjamin Ackerman and Joseph Witt&#45;<lb/>&#45;enberg&#44; applicants.<lb/></p>
            <p>The subjects taught have been&#44;<lb/> in the Junior Department&#44; Isaiah<lb/> and Talmud and in the Prepar&#45;<lb/>&#45;atory Department Nehemiah and<lb/> Mishnah.  Besides this the classes<lb/> have been required to attend the<lb/> lectures which have been delivered<lb/> on Sunday mornings during the<lb/> month.  The attendance and pro&#45;<lb/>&#45;gress have been quite satisfactory<lb/> considering the extremely warm<lb/> and unpleasant weather which have&#44;<lb/> for the greater part&#44; prevailed.<lb/>  In concluding this report I would respectfully<lb/> request you to kindly dispense me<lb/> from delivering the lecture next<lb/> Sunday morning and also to<lb/> grant me leave of absence for a<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>few weeks.  I have not felt well<lb/> for some time&#44; my strength&#44; I am<lb/> afraid&#44; is not adequate for proper<lb/> attention to duty and my physic&#45;<lb/>&#45;ian advises me to leave the city.<lb/>  The best arrangement would be to sub&#45;<lb/>&#45;stitute some other lecturer for me<lb/> next Sunday&#44; Dr H. P. Mendes will<lb/> be in the city&#44; and to give me the<lb/> closing lecture of the term.  By that<lb/> time&#44; I hope to be&#44; the Lord permitting<lb/> in better sorts and able to attend<lb/> properly to my duties.  Will you<lb/> kindly write at once advising me<lb/> of what disposition you make in this<lb/> matter.  I remain<lb/> very respectfully yours<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            <p>N. Y. July 15th 5650 								Preceptor<lb/></p>
            </body>
